t: To the chief Musician, A Psalm of David.
The*p heavens declare the glory of God; and the firmament sheweth his handywork.
Day*p unto day uttereth speech, and night unto night sheweth knowledge.
There*p is no speech nor language, where their voice is not heard.
Their*p line is gone out through all the earth, and their words to the end of the world. In them hath he set a tabernacle for the sun,
Which*p is as a bridegroom coming out of his chamber, and rejoiceth as a strong man to run a race.
His*p going forth is from the end of the heaven, and his circuit unto the ends of it: and there is nothing hid from the heat thereof.
The*p law of the Lord*s is perfect, converting the soul: the testimony of the Lord*s is sure, making wise the simple.
The*p statutes of the Lord*s are right, rejoicing the heart: the commandment of the Lord*s is pure, enlightening the eyes.
The*p fear of the Lord*s is clean, enduring for ever: the judgments of the Lord*s are true and righteous altogether.
More*p to be desired are they than gold, yea, than much fine gold: sweeter also than honey and the honeycomb.
Moreover*p by them is thy servant warned: and in keeping of them there is great reward.
Who*p can understand his errors? cleanse thou me from secret faults.
Keep*p back thy servant also from presumptuous sins; let them not have dominion over me: then shall I be upright, and I shall be innocent from the great transgression.
Let*p the words of my mouth, and the meditation of my heart, be acceptable in thy sight, O Lord,*s my strength, and my redeemer.
